{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b0f53b79-cd23-48ff-8188-406217546d94","content":"No worries — here's how to configure it. Create a `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout (the standard for local MCP servers).\n- **`command` / `args`** — Uses `dotnet run` to build and launch your project.\n- If you publish a self-contained executable instead, point `command` directly at the binary and drop the `args`.\n- You can add `\"env\": { \"KEY\": \"value\" }` for environment variables your server needs.\n\nOnce saved, VS Code will detect it automatically and your MCP tools will appear in Copilot agent mode.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"475f3955-f412-499f-9f39-c3968cf89abd","outputTokens":247,"requestId":"CBC0:331FF:18929AA:1BC93D7:69FE8940"},"id":"c045c33c-4e59-49ae-bebf-08f2067bc6f9","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:09:29.256Z","parentId":"e2c99cc7-21f2-4453-a9b9-e03b91dba8b9"}
